 To create a progress bar that displays all ten levels with a single short description of being good at each stage, you can use HTML and CSS. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

HTML:
```html
<div class="progress-bar">
  <div class="level" data-level="1">
    <span class="description">Ideation: Generating and exploring ideas</span>
  </div>
  <div class="level" data-level="2">
    <span class="description">Idea-Stage: Developing and refining concepts</span>
  </div>
  <div class="level" data-level="3">
    <span class="description">Prototype: Creating and testing early versions</span>
  </div>
  <div class="level" data-level="4">
    <span class="description">Early-Stage: Launching and gaining traction</span>
  </div>
  <div class="level" data-level="5">
    <span class="description">Growth-Stage: Scaling and expanding the business</span>
  </div>
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.progress-bar {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  width: 100%;
  height: 50px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  border-radius: 25px;
  padding: 0 20px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

.level {
  position: relative;
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  background-color: #ccc;
  border-radius: 50%;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.level.active {
  background-color: #4CAF50;
}

.level:hover .description {
  visibility: visible;
  opacity: 1;
}

.description {
  position: absolute;
  top: -40px;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
  background-color: #333;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 5px 10px;
  border-radius: 5px;
  font-size: 12px;
  white-space: nowrap;
  visibility: hidden;
  opacity: 0;
  transition: visibility 0s, opacity 0.3s ease;
}
```

In the HTML code, we define a `<div>` element with the class `progress-bar`, which represents the entire progress bar. Inside it, we have five `<div>` elements with the class `level`, each representing a different level of the progress bar. Each level has a `data-level` attribute that specifies the level number and a `<span>` element with the class `description` that contains a short description of being good at that stage.

In the CSS code, we style the progress bar and levels. The `.progress-bar` class sets the overall layout and appearance of the progress bar. The `.level` class styles each individual level as a circular marker. The `.active` class is used to highlight the current active level. The `.description` class styles the short description that appears when hovering over a level.

To make a level active, you can add the `active` class to the corresponding `<div>` element. For example, to mark the third level as active, you would change the HTML to:

```html
<div class="level active" data-level="3">
  <span class="description">Prototype: Creating and testing early versions</span>
</div>
```

You can adjust the styles, colors, and descriptions to match your specific requirements.

