 Here's a simple and progressive way to create a table with 10 levels, allowing people to select their level and indicate how well they are doing at each stage for the question "Do we clearly and comprehensively understand our customers' and stakeholders' values and needs, and have we prioritized them?":

HTML:
```html
<table class="progress-table">
  <tr>
    <th>Level</th>
    <th>1</th>
    <th>2</th>
    <th>3</th>
    <th>4</th>
    <th>5</th>
    <th>6</th>
    <th>7</th>
    <th>8</th>
    <th>9</th>
    <th>10</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Understanding Customers & Stakeholders</td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="1"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="2"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="3"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="4"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="5"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="6"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="7"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="8"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="9"></td>
    <td><input type="radio" name="level" value="10"></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<div id="result"></div>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const radioButtons = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="radio"]');
const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

radioButtons.forEach(radio => {
  radio.addEventListener('change', () => {
    const selectedLevel = parseInt(document.querySelector('input[name="level"]:checked').value);
    let resultText = '';

    if (selectedLevel <= 3) {
      resultText = 'Just starting to understand customers and stakeholders';
    } else if (selectedLevel <= 6) {
      resultText = 'Making progress in understanding customers and stakeholders';
    } else if (selectedLevel <= 8) {
      resultText = 'Doing well in understanding customers and stakeholders';
    } else {
      resultText = 'Excellent understanding of customers and stakeholders';
    }

    resultDiv.textContent = resultText;
  });
});
```

CSS:
```css
.progress-table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
}

.progress-table th,
.progress-table td {
  padding: 8px;
  text-align: center;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

.progress-table th {
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

#result {
  margin-top: 20px;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

In this example, we have a table with 10 levels represented by radio buttons. The user can select their level by clicking on the corresponding radio button.

When a radio button is selected, the JavaScript code listens for the `change` event and retrieves the selected level value. It then determines the appropriate result text based on the selected level:
- Levels 1-3: "Just starting to understand customers and stakeholders"
- Levels 4-6: "Making progress in understanding customers and stakeholders"
- Levels 7-8: "Doing well in understanding customers and stakeholders"
- Levels 9-10: "Excellent understanding of customers and stakeholders"

The result text is then displayed in the `<div>` element with the ID `result`.

The CSS code styles the table and result text to make it visually appealing.

You can customize the level ranges, result texts, and styles to match your specific requirements.

